---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const blogContent = `
<p>Imagine a 3D grid that wraps around in every direction — a torus. Every
vertex has three outgoing edges: one along each axis. The question is whether
you can color those edges with three colors so that each color, taken alone,
traces a single Hamiltonian cycle through the entire graph. This is the
Directed Hamiltonian Torus Decomposition problem, posed by
<a href="https://cs.stanford.edu/~knuth/papers/claude.pdf">Knuth</a>
in early 2026.</p>

<p>Constructions exist for odd grid sizes and even sizes ≥ 8, but the
small even cases — 4×4×4 and 6×6×6 — fell through the cracks. We found
valid decompositions for both, and the Lean 4 kernel
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/blob/main/paper/torus_decomposition.pdf">proves they work</a>.</p>

<p>But the paper skips the most interesting engineering problem: how do you actually
<em>find</em> a working configuration when the search space is
6<sup>215</sup> ≈ 10<sup>167</sup> states?</p>

<p class="paper-ref">📄 Our paper: <a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/blob/main/paper/torus_decomposition.pdf"><em>Machine-Checked Proofs of the m=4 and m=6 Directed Hamiltonian Torus Decompositions</em></a></p>

<h2>The Bottleneck: O(N) Energy Evaluation</h2>

<p>Simulated Annealing needs an energy function it can evaluate millions of times.
For this problem, each evaluation has to check whether three color subgraphs form
valid Hamiltonian cycles across all <em>m</em>³ vertices.</p>

<p>The naive approach recomputes the entire board on every mutation: trace all
three color graphs, count components, check in-degrees. For <em>m</em>=6 that's
216 vertices × 3 colors per evaluation. At millions of iterations, this is a
death sentence for throughput.</p>

<h2>Getting the Energy Function Right</h2>

<p>Before optimizing speed, we had to get correctness right — and the first
version was subtly wrong.</p>

<p>Each color subgraph has out-degree 1 at every vertex by construction (each
vertex assigns exactly one outgoing arc per color). But the <em>in-degree</em>
is not guaranteed. A functional graph with variable in-degree can have directed
cycles with trees feeding into them. Our first energy function counted only the
number of cycles per color and happily assigned <em>E</em> = 0 to
non-Hamiltonian topologies.</p>

<p>The fix: count weakly connected components <em>and</em> vertices with
in-degree ≠ 1. The energy becomes:</p>

<pre><code>E(σ) = Σ (components_c - 1) + Σ (vertices with in-degree ≠ 1)</code></pre>

<p>This is zero if and only if each color subgraph is a single Hamiltonian cycle.
No false zeros.</p>

<h2>The 12× Speedup: O(N) → O(1)</h2>

<p>The SA mutation operator is simple: pick a random vertex, change its
permutation to one of five alternatives, accept or reject via Metropolis.</p>

<p>The baseline engine recomputed <em>E</em> from scratch on every mutation.
The incremental engine changed a single vertex, updated the affected in-degree
counts in O(1), and recounted cycles only for the colors touched by that
vertex. Rejected mutations were rolled back in place — no allocations, no
copies.</p>

<p>This turned an O(<em>m</em>³) evaluation into an O(1) delta update.</p>

<table>
<thead>
<tr><th>Case</th><th>Engine</th><th>Time to solution</th></tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr><td><em>m</em>=4</td><td>Baseline (full recompute)</td><td>93 s</td></tr>
<tr><td><em>m</em>=4</td><td>Incremental (O(1) delta)</td><td>3.1 s</td></tr>
<tr><td><em>m</em>=6</td><td>Incremental (O(1) delta)</td><td>99.5 s</td></tr>
</tbody>
</table>

<p>Same algorithm, same hyperparameters. The only difference was per-iteration
throughput. To validate the incremental engine, we ran a 300,000-step fuzz test
asserting exact agreement with full recalculation at every mutation.
Zero discrepancies.</p>

<h2>The Cooling Schedule</h2>

<p>Standard exponential cooling stalls on this problem. The energy landscape has
deep local minima — states where two colors form perfect Hamiltonian cycles but
the third fragments. A monotonic schedule gets trapped.</p>

<p>We used non-monotonic cooling: when the best energy stagnates for <em>W</em>
iterations, reset the temperature to max(1, <em>E</em><sub>best</sub><sup>2/5</sup>)
and double the stagnation window. The reheat is proportional to the current best
energy — gentle near the goal, aggressive when far away.</p>

<p>The same parameters (T₀ = 50, α = 0.999998, <em>E</em><sup>2/5</sup> reheat)
solved both <em>m</em>=4 and <em>m</em>=6 without any per-problem tuning.</p>

<h2>Bridging TypeScript to Lean 4</h2>

<p>A heuristic search engine written in TypeScript is fast, but it is not a proof.
Runtime bugs, off-by-one errors, or edge cases in the energy function could
produce witnesses that <em>look</em> valid but aren't.</p>

<p>That's why the final step is a clean handoff to Lean 4. The TypeScript engine
acts as an oracle: it does the heavy lifting to find the array, then outputs the
raw witness. That witness is hardcoded into a Lean script, and Lean's
<code>decide</code> tactic verifies the topology from first principles. The
search engine and the proof share zero code.</p>

<p>For <em>m</em>=6, the kernel checks 46,656 pairwise injectivity comparisons per
color and verifies 216-step orbits. We had to set <code>maxHeartbeats</code> to
4 × 10<sup>8</sup> (roughly 100× the default) to give the kernel enough time.
It compiles in 57 seconds on an Apple M4.</p>

<h2>What I Learned</h2>

<p><strong>Energy function design matters more than schedule tuning.</strong>
A wrong energy function means the search converges to the wrong thing.
No amount of cooling schedule wizardry fixes that.</p>

<p><strong>Incremental evaluation is the scaling lever.</strong>
The 12× throughput gain from O(1) delta updates was worth more than any
hyperparameter change. For <em>m</em>=6, the baseline engine would have needed
hours.</p>

<p><strong>The search and the proof are independent artifacts.</strong>
The solver can be wrong, buggy, or nondeterministic. The Lean kernel doesn't
care — it only checks the witness. This separation is the entire point of
formal verification, and it's liberating as an engineer: you can be fast and
sloppy in the search, as long as you're rigorous in the proof.</p>

<hr>

<p><em>The formal paper is available as a
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/blob/main/paper/torus_decomposition.pdf">PDF</a>.
The SA engine is in
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/tree/main/src/math">src/math/</a>,
and the Lean 4 proofs are in
<a href="https://github.com/bneb/perqed/tree/main/src/lean">src/lean/</a>.</em></p>
`;
---

<BaseLayout title="Finding Needles in a 6^215 Haystack — Perqed" activeNav="blog">

  <article class="article">
    <div class="container">
      <div class="prose">
        <header class="article-header">
          <div class="article-meta">
            <time>March 15, 2026</time>
            <span class="sep">·</span>
            <span>8 min read</span>
          </div>
          <h1>Finding Needles in a 6<sup>215</sup> Haystack</h1>
        </header>

        <div set:html={blogContent} />
      </div>
    </div>
  </article>

</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .article {
    padding: 64px 0 80px;
  }

  .article-header {
    margin-bottom: 40px;
  }

  .article-meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 8px;
    font-family: var(--font-mono);
    font-size: 0.78rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin-bottom: 16px;
  }

  .sep {
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .article :global(.paper-ref) {
    font-size: 0.88rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    padding-left: 12px;
    margin: 24px 0;
  }

  /* Tables inside prose */
  .article :global(table) {
    width: 100%;
    border-collapse: collapse;
    margin: 24px 0;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .article :global(th) {
    text-align: left;
    font-weight: 600;
    padding: 10px 16px;
    border-bottom: 2px solid var(--border-color);
    font-size: 0.84rem;
    color: var(--text-secondary);
  }

  .article :global(td) {
    padding: 10px 16px;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border-subtle);
    vertical-align: top;
  }

  .article :global(tr:last-child td) {
    border-bottom: none;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .article { padding: 32px 0 48px; }

    .article :global(table) {
      font-size: 0.8rem;
    }

    .article :global(th),
    .article :global(td) {
      padding: 8px 10px;
    }
  }
</style>
